Guests should get access only to the Internet. None of the Corporate resources.
I set up VLANs to separate the two zones. Configured a Layer 3 switch to route between them. Then wrote an extended ACL to enforce the actual policy.

Note: This is the manual version of what real Intent-Based Networking (IBN) platforms automate. Tools like Cisco DNA Center take a plain-English rule and translate it into configs across the network. 
I did that translation myself, by hand.

The video below shows the simulation. 
Case 1: Guest tries to reach the Internet —> Works fine. 
Case 2: Guest tries to reach Corporate —> Blocked at the L3 switch.
Case 3: Corporate tries to reach the Guest... What do you think happens?

Here's the catch: the ACL is one-directional. Corporate can reach the Guest PC anytime it wants. The isolation only goes one way.
